<DocsLayout title="Knowledge Types" description="The structured knowledge types stored in Engrams.">
  <h1>Knowledge Types</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    Engrams stores structured knowledge across several distinct types. Each type maps to a database table
    and is managed via specific <code>engrams</code> CLI subcommands.
  </p>

  <h2>Product Context</h2>
  <p>
    A single JSON document representing the high-level, relatively stable description of your project —
    goals, architecture overview, key features, and tech stack.
    Updated with <code>engrams product-context update</code>; retrieved with <code>engrams product-context get</code>.
  </p>
  <div class="callout note">
    <strong>When to use it:</strong> Think of this as your project's README in structured form.
    Update it when you make a major architectural pivot or add a significant new feature area.
  </div>

  <h2>Active Context</h2>
  <p>
    A single JSON document representing the <em>current</em> state of work — the present focus,
    open questions, next steps, and recent changes. Updated frequently during a session.
    Updated with <code>engrams active-context update</code>; retrieved with <code>engrams active-context get</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Decisions</h2>
  <p>
    Individual architectural or implementation choices (ADRs) with a summary, rationale, implementation
    details, and optional tags. Decisions are the most commonly used knowledge type.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`Decision #7: Use JWT tokens for stateless authentication
Rationale: Scales better than sessions, works with microservices
Tags: auth, security, architecture`}</code></pre>
  <p>Supports fast keyword and phrase queries via SQLite FTS5 index: <code>engrams decision search &lt;query&gt;</code>.</p>

  <h2>Progress</h2>
  <p>
    Task tracking with hierarchical parent/child support. Managed via <code>engrams progress</code>. Each entry has a status
    (e.g., <code>TODO</code>, <code>InProgress</code>, <code>Done</code>) and
    an optional parent ID for subtask relationships.
  </p>

  <h2>System Patterns</h2>
  <p>
    Recurring architectural or design patterns observed or used in the project. Unlike decisions
    (which capture <em>why</em>), patterns capture <em>how</em>. Managed via <code>engrams pattern</code>.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`Pattern #3: Token validation middleware
Description: All API routes validate JWT in Authorization header
             using the shared auth.middleware module`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Custom Data</h2>
  <p>
    A flexible category/key/value store for any project knowledge that doesn't fit the above types:
    glossaries, technical specifications, config values, or team guidelines. Managed via <code>engrams custom</code>.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`Category: config
Key: "api_host"
Value: "localhost:8080"`}</code></pre>
  <p>Supports custom value FTS search: <code>engrams custom search &lt;query&gt;</code>.</p>

  <h2>Context Links (Relationships)</h2>
  <p>
    Explicit edges in the knowledge graph. A link connects two entities with a named relationship type using the <code>engrams link</code> command:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Relationship type</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>implements</code></td><td>Pattern implements a Decision</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>related_to</code></td><td>General association</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>tracks</code></td><td>Progress item tracks a Decision</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>blocks</code></td><td>One item blocks another</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>clarifies</code></td><td>Custom data clarifies a Decision</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>depends_on</code></td><td>Dependency relationship</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>supersedes</code></td><td>A new decision supersedes an old one</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>resolves</code></td><td>A progress item resolves a Decision</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</DocsLayout>

